WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:08.400
[mournful choir music playing]

2
00:00:39.800 --> 00:00:41.240
{\an8}[buzzer sounds]

3
00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:43.480
{\an8}[busy chatter]

4
00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:44.560
{\an8}Oh.

5
00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:49.640
{\an8}[button beeps]

6
00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:52.520
{\an8}[man] Do you work here?

7
00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:55.440
{\an8}- Um. I'm a visitor.
- [man] Right.

8
00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:02.200
{\an8}Right. Do you wanna
just come through for a second?

9
00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:05.160
{\an8}[Briony] Sorry. I'm a bit late.

10
00:01:05.240 --> 00:01:09.040
{\an8}That's all right.
I saw you coming up on the cameras.

11
00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:10.560
{\an8}He's being brought down.

12
00:01:11.480 --> 00:01:14.320
{\an8}Um. I heard he was involved
in a violent incident.

13
00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:17.240
{\an8}- [clicks tongue] How'd you hear that?
- It was reported up.

14
00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:20.320
{\an8}- That would be useful to see--
- Is that… relevant?

15
00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:21.960
{\an8}To what you'll assess?

16
00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:24.480
{\an8}I'd like to see it.

17
00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:28.440
{\an8}Okay. I'll. uh. fire up the megaport.

18
00:01:37.520 --> 00:01:39.520
Yeah. he's been pretty quiet.

19
00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:42.480
Don't know if that's relevant.

20
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.640
If what I think and observe
is relevant to what you assess.

21
00:01:48.280 --> 00:01:50.520
- [machine beeps]
- [man] Here we go.

22
00:01:57.320 --> 00:02:00.000
- Yeah. It's just bruising and scratching.
- [Briony] I read the report.

23
00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:02.560
- [man] Both blame the other.
- [Briony] I know. I read the report.

24
00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:08.040
You're on… five visits?

25
00:02:08.800 --> 00:02:10.080
- Yes.
- [man] Mm.

26
00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:11.960
Know what you're gonna say in the report?

27
00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:14.360
I wouldn't be here if I knew that.

28
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.080
Well. the other one of you.
He only needed three. so--

29
00:02:18.160 --> 00:02:19.400
You can't say any more.

30
00:02:19.480 --> 00:02:22.240
It's important I don't know
what the other psychologist says.

31
00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:23.720
does. or thinks.

32
00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:31.440
It's about making the <i>right </i>assessment.
not the fastest.

33
00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:35.640
- [man] Sorry. I'm just being an idiot.
- No. I did… That's just the way I work.

34
00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:42.520
Right. That's Jamie in place.

35
00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:43.760
I'll take you through.

36
00:02:44.680 --> 00:02:47.280
I need to get a hot chocolate
from the machine.

37
00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:48.560
[man] I remember.

38
00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:06.680
[machine whirring]

39
00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:32.040
[boy screaming in distance]

40
00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:33.480
Get off me!

41
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.520
No! You get off!

42
00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:39.680
Yeah. we've got a torture lab
in the basement.

43
00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:42.440
Government approved. All very hush-hush.

44
00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:44.040
What are they?

45
00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:46.440
[Briony] He likes his hot chocolate
with marshmallows on.

46
00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:49.520
You must mean business.
Never done them before.

47
00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:52.480
- [alarm blaring]
- That was. uh. Mark. I think.

48
00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:55.560
Radiator burns all over him. poor kid.

49
00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:59.040
I don't know what he did
to get here. though.

50
00:03:59.840 --> 00:04:02.240
He's not famous like your Jamie.

51
00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:05.520
- Come on!
- Two of us on the way now.

52
00:04:07.920 --> 00:04:09.360
Right. You know where I am.

53
00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:16.680
- You okay?
- [Briony] Yes.

54
00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:21.240
- Hi. Jamie.
- [Jamie] Hi.

55
00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:24.240
- You need us. we're here.
- [Briony] Yes.

56
00:04:24.320 --> 00:04:26.160
- Same goes for you. Jamie.
- [Jamie] Yeah.

57
00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:27.920
[guard] We'll be watching. okay?

58
00:04:31.560 --> 00:04:32.840
- [door closes]
- [Jamie sniffles]

59
00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:35.200
Hot chocolate.

60
00:04:35.280 --> 00:04:36.720
Spri… Sprinkles?

61
00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:37.920
Lots of them.

62
00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:41.280
You remembered. Thank you.

63
00:04:41.800 --> 00:04:44.960
And I saved you half my sandwich
in case you were hungry.

64
00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:46.040
What is it?

65
00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:48.000
[Briony] Cheese and pickle.

66
00:04:48.920 --> 00:04:50.360
No tomatoes?

67
00:04:50.440 --> 00:04:52.600
[Briony] Tomatoes don't go very well
with pickle.

68
00:04:53.120 --> 00:04:54.240
No salad?

69
00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:56.480
Would I do that to you?

70
00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:02.600
There's no tomatoes. No salad.
There's just cheese and pickle.

71
00:05:02.680 --> 00:05:06.120
- Do you want it? I'll save it for later.
- No. I'll have it.

72
00:05:06.200 --> 00:05:09.920
Ah. I… I don't know about pickle.
though. but… I'll have it.

73
00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:12.440
[sighs]

74
00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:15.560
- Did you make it?
- Yes.

75
00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:18.520
- You make butties. do you?
- What. you think that's weird?

76
00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:21.440
No. My mum makes 'em.

77
00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:23.320
Well. that makes two of us. then.

78
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:26.960
This is nice.

79
00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:27.960
It's a bit hot.

80
00:05:28.520 --> 00:05:29.760
I don't mind hot.

81
00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:34.360
[sniffles]

82
00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:39.120
- You're looking better than last time.
- What's that supposed to mean?

83
00:05:39.640 --> 00:05:41.600
You've just got some of your color back.

84
00:05:42.440 --> 00:05:45.040
- You sound like a granny.
- [chuckles] Do I?

85
00:05:45.120 --> 00:05:47.720
"Oh. you got your color back.
You can't have been that ill."

86
00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:50.560
- [Briony] That's a good voice.
- No.

87
00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:54.160
[Briony] Do you see
your grandparents much?

88
00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:58.080
- Well. not recently. no.
- [Briony] No. I meant before all this.

89
00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:00.520
Yeah. a bit.

90
00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:03.880
My dad's side… my dad's mum and dad.
My mum didn't get on with hers.

91
00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:05.680
[Briony] Yeah. we spoke about that.

92
00:06:06.520 --> 00:06:09.520
- So. what are your dad's parents like?
- [clears throat]

93
00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:13.040
[sighs] I don't know. Like him.

94
00:06:13.560 --> 00:06:14.960
[Briony] Well. what does that mean?

95
00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:20.320
They like things as they like them.
"No gravy. Such a shame."

96
00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:23.840
Or. "I like a slice with my dinner
if you've got one in. Amanda."

97
00:06:23.920 --> 00:06:26.320
[chuckles] A slice… A slice of what?

98
00:06:26.840 --> 00:06:29.000
[scoffs] Bread.

99
00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:32.520
- You're posh. aren't ya?
- No. I'm just not from where you're from.

100
00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:35.120
Well. what do you call bread
if you don't call it a slice?

101
00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:36.480
Mm. bread?

102
00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:38.840
[both laugh]

103
00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:40.000
You're posh.

104
00:06:40.520 --> 00:06:42.440
If it makes you happy that I am.
Jamie. then I am.

105
00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:45.520
Well. what do you call your grandad?
Bet you call him "Grandpa."

106
00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:47.080
- I do not.
- I bet you do.

107
00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:48.600
I call him "Pop-pop."

108
00:06:48.680 --> 00:06:49.680
What?

109
00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:51.240
Do ya?

110
00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:54.120
- Yes. I do.
- Wow! [laughs]

111
00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:57.480
- Jesus. I've not heard that one before.
- I don't know why.

112
00:06:57.560 --> 00:07:00.600
Okay. Maybe he asked me
to call him that. I'm not sure.

113
00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:02.800
- God. you're really posh.
- [sighs]

114
00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:04.640
[Jamie inhales sharply]

115
00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:06.880
Are you not gonna try the sandwich?

116
00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:10.160
I'll have it later. It's just… the pickle.

117
00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:12.360
Hate it.

118
00:07:12.440 --> 00:07:13.600
You hate it?

119
00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:16.400
- Oh. I really messed up. then.
- Yeah. you did.

120
00:07:16.480 --> 00:07:17.520
Okay.

121
00:07:19.680 --> 00:07:21.440
So. can we talk a bit about you?

122
00:07:22.080 --> 00:07:24.520
You see a lot of your dad
in your grandad. do you?

123
00:07:25.480 --> 00:07:26.520
Yeah. I don't know.

124
00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:30.320
Is it just what they say.
or how they do things?

125
00:07:30.400 --> 00:07:32.360
What's your dad and his dad like?

126
00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:34.160
Men.

127
00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:39.240
Okay. Well. would "masculine"
be an okay word to use?

128
00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:41.160
[Jamie] <i>You </i>used it.

129
00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.680
When I hear the word "masculine."
I think they can mend things.

130
00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:47.840
They like to make things.

131
00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:51.240
They like sports.
They like going to the pub.

132
00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:53.240
[Jamie] Yeah.

133
00:07:53.840 --> 00:07:56.160
Not the pub. but. yeah.

134
00:07:56.240 --> 00:07:57.800
Your dad doesn't go to the pub?

135
00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:00.560
[Jamie clicks tongue] No. not… not really.

136
00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:02.640
Not as much as my pop-pop.

137
00:08:03.160 --> 00:08:06.000
- Not gonna let me forget that. are you?
- [Jamie chuckles] No.

138
00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:09.800
So. your grandad's
more of a pub man. is he?

139
00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:14.320
[Jamie] I dunno. He…
He's not around that much anymore.

140
00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:15.280
How much?

141
00:08:17.600 --> 00:08:19.120
Every other Sunday. maybe.

142
00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:21.560
Sometimes in the week when they're both…

143
00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:25.000
Mum and Dad are both working.
but that's more Granny.

144
00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:27.680
A bit more in the holidays.

145
00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:30.680
- We went to Tenerife with them once.
- On holiday?

146
00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:33.440
No. banana picking.

147
00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:35.320
- [chuckles]
- [scoffs]

148
00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:38.600
- Obviously it was on holiday.
- Okay. [laughs]

149
00:08:39.120 --> 00:08:43.960
I don't think I've ever heard anyone
use banana picking in a comeback.

150
00:08:44.480 --> 00:08:46.840
- [laughs. sighs]
- [Jamie chuckles softly]

151
00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:52.080
I suppose the other thing I think about
when I hear the word "masculine"

152
00:08:52.160 --> 00:08:53.840
would be the way that masculine men--

153
00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:56.200
This started 'cause I said
you sounded like a granny.

154
00:08:56.280 --> 00:08:58.080
- [Briony] What?
- [sighs]

155
00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.320
This all started
because I said you sounded like a granny.

156
00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:04.600
And now you're just going on
about masculine stuff.

157
00:09:04.680 --> 00:09:05.760
[Briony] Yes.

158
00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:08.240
The first time you came.
you had actual questions.

159
00:09:08.320 --> 00:09:11.200
"Is this right. Jamie?
Do you know whether this is wrong. Jamie?"

160
00:09:11.720 --> 00:09:14.680
- Now you're just chatting shit.
- I hope I'm not.

161
00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:17.200
Well. you are.
because the first time you're all.

162
00:09:17.280 --> 00:09:20.400
"If an adult guinea pig eats
one of its kids. is that normal or weird?"

163
00:09:20.480 --> 00:09:22.640
- And now you're. "What do you call bread?"
- Come on.

164
00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:24.280
- I'm interested.
- It feels like a trick.

165
00:09:24.360 --> 00:09:26.280
Trick? Trick into what?

166
00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:29.160
My dad's okay.

167
00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:31.360
All right?

168
00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:33.920
Okay. I know.

169
00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:35.960
Just talking about him.

170
00:09:36.840 --> 00:09:38.120
There isn't a need.

171
00:09:40.720 --> 00:09:44.240
Fine. if that's how you feel.
But I'm not trying to trick you.

172
00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:47.760
[sighs]

173
00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:50.400
- And now I've pissed you off.
- [Briony] No.

174
00:09:53.480 --> 00:09:56.560
Can I see your notes?
What you've got written down about me?

175
00:09:56.640 --> 00:09:58.680
- Do you see me writing?
- [Jamie] You must write stuff.

176
00:09:58.760 --> 00:09:59.960
Yes.

177
00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:02.720
[Jamie] Can I see what you wrote?
What you've written?

178
00:10:03.240 --> 00:10:04.440
Of course you can't.

179
00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:08.480
- The lawyers have said you work for us.
- That's not what they say. Jamie.

180
00:10:08.560 --> 00:10:11.360
And I know that because I asked them
the last time you said that to me.

181
00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:13.200
[Jamie] You talk to them?

182
00:10:13.880 --> 00:10:16.600
I explained. I've been employed
by your team. but I don't work for you.

183
00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:19.120
- [Jamie] What do you tell them?
- I'm writing an independent--

184
00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:23.760
- [Jamie] What do they say to you?
- A presentence offense report.

185
00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:26.800
Which the judge will read
to get an understanding of you

186
00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:29.280
and your understanding
of the charges. Okay?

187
00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:30.560
[Jamie sighs]

188
00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:35.920
All I want to do is talk to you. Jamie.
and have you talk to me.

189
00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:40.160
Yes. I've asked
some straightforward questions.

190
00:10:40.240 --> 00:10:41.320
- But I think…
- [yawns]

191
00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:42.640
[Briony] Am I boring you?

192
00:10:43.160 --> 00:10:44.800
- No.
- [Briony] Okay.

193
00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:52.120
I think you.
and everyone else for that matter.

194
00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:55.320
are far more complex
than straightforward questions allow for.

195
00:10:56.680 --> 00:10:59.520
We had a good conversation last time.
Can we try that again?

196
00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:01.640
What did we talk about last time?

197
00:11:01.720 --> 00:11:04.520
We spoke about your friends.
your sister. your mum. We went--

198
00:11:04.600 --> 00:11:06.960
- Can't remember saying anything about 'em.
- Well. you did.

199
00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:10.480
How you feel about them. How Lisa's doing.
What you think your mum thinks of you.

200
00:11:10.560 --> 00:11:13.800
- Now you wanna talk about my dad?
- I want to talk about lots of things.

201
00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:18.680
[Jamie sighs]

202
00:11:18.760 --> 00:11:21.520
I could tell you questions that
I wrote down to talk to you about today.

203
00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:22.760
If that helps.

204
00:11:23.600 --> 00:11:25.040
All right. Yeah.

205
00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:29.720
Okay. Well. I wanted
to talk about the fight you had.

206
00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:32.640
- That was nothing.
- I was interested why you got in a fight.

207
00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:34.680
- He hit me first.
- Why?

208
00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:37.960
Because we've had beef over stuff.

209
00:11:38.480 --> 00:11:40.280
It doesn't matter.
It wasn't a proper fight.

210
00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:42.560
- It's not that interesting?
- It's not.

211
00:11:42.640 --> 00:11:44.400
Okay. let's move on.

212
00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:47.240
- What? I'm in charge now. am I?
- Mm. Maybe.

213
00:11:50.920 --> 00:11:54.960
I also wrote down that I wanted to talk
to you about what being a man feels like.

214
00:11:55.960 --> 00:11:57.840
You want a cock and balls. do ya?

215
00:11:59.480 --> 00:12:02.680
I'm interested in what being a man
feels like for you.

216
00:12:03.560 --> 00:12:04.440
I dunno.

217
00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:06.800
It's too big a question. right?

218
00:12:07.360 --> 00:12:09.280
And the fight's too small a question.

219
00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:13.160
Which is why it's more useful
for me to see where the conversation goes

220
00:12:13.240 --> 00:12:17.440
and steer it a bit into what you think of
your dad and your grandad. for instance.

221
00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:19.160
The type of men you think they are.

222
00:12:19.240 --> 00:12:23.080
Rather than saying. "So. Jamie.
what do you think being a man feels like?"

223
00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:24.840
[Jamie chuckles]

224
00:12:24.920 --> 00:12:27.480
"So. Jamie. what do you think
being a man feels like?"

225
00:12:27.560 --> 00:12:28.840
It's not a trick.

226
00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:33.600
It's just a conversation.

227
00:12:37.400 --> 00:12:40.320
So. do you think it would be okay
if we speak about your dad?

228
00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:46.760
Can I just see your notes?
What you wrote. how you wrote it?

229
00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:47.680
Nope.

230
00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:49.840
You're not that in charge.

231
00:12:52.760 --> 00:12:54.480
Does your dad like his job?

232
00:12:55.240 --> 00:12:57.520
He fixes toilets. What do you think?

233
00:12:58.320 --> 00:12:59.240
He works hard.

234
00:12:59.760 --> 00:13:03.760
Long hours. You get the best money
from emergency plumbing out of hours.

235
00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:04.840
Is he funny?

236
00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:06.400
Sometimes.

237
00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:07.360
Loving?

238
00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:09.960
- No. that's weird.
- Angry?

239
00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:11.880
I suppose.

240
00:13:11.960 --> 00:13:13.320
How angry does he get?

241
00:13:13.800 --> 00:13:15.000
He's never hit me.

242
00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:16.400
Okay. go on.

243
00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:18.320
Go on what?

244
00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.560
- Is that what this is about?
- Why do you call him angry?

245
00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:24.120
He just gets mad. We all do.

246
00:13:24.200 --> 00:13:27.800
Okay. That's okay.
He's just angry in a normal way.

247
00:13:29.400 --> 00:13:35.160
Well. he's pulled a shed down once
when he was in a proper rager. but…

248
00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:37.880
[clears throat] …that's as bad as it gets.

249
00:13:37.960 --> 00:13:39.240
Were you frightened?

250
00:13:40.360 --> 00:13:43.760
No. I… I thought it was quite funny
at the time.

251
00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:47.520
Lisa did too. Then Mum sent us upstairs.

252
00:13:49.200 --> 00:13:50.960
He's not like that most of the time.

253
00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:53.120
Hardly ever.

254
00:13:54.520 --> 00:13:56.320
What does he do when he's not working?

255
00:13:58.160 --> 00:13:59.920
It just feels like you're testing him.

256
00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.560
No. I'm just interested
in your view of him.

257
00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:06.240
He's a big presence in your life.
He was your appropriate adult.

258
00:14:06.320 --> 00:14:08.720
Yeah. 'cause… he doesn't judge.

259
00:14:09.560 --> 00:14:11.360
He… He's a kind person.

260
00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:13.120
That's good to know.

261
00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:16.600
So. what does he do when he's not working?

262
00:14:18.480 --> 00:14:20.960
He basically likes all sport.

263
00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:25.040
My mum always said if he'd watch
lawn bowls. he'd make it fun.

264
00:14:25.120 --> 00:14:27.000
Would you watch lawn bowls with him?

265
00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:30.120
No. it's… it's not for me.

266
00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:31.440
Are you not into sport?

267
00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:33.480
- No.
- None of it?

268
00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:39.480
Yeah. I'm… I'm not good at much.
but… I'm really good at getting out of PE.

269
00:14:40.040 --> 00:14:41.320
How do you do that. then?

270
00:14:42.680 --> 00:14:45.480
Um. headaches. Hurt my leg.

271
00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:46.920
Funny tummy.

272
00:14:47.600 --> 00:14:51.000
[sighs] "Sir. I feel dizzy.
Can I sit down?" That sort of thing.

273
00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:53.160
What did… does your dad make of that?

274
00:14:54.680 --> 00:14:56.240
He. um… He didn't…

275
00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.080
[clears throat] He doesn't…
He doesn't know.

276
00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:04.160
He knew I wasn't sporty
or anything like that.

277
00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:07.000
[sighs]

278
00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.680
I… I used to. uh…
He used to take me to football.

279
00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:12.680
[clears throat] This…

280
00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:17.160
This football thing on… on Saturdays.

281
00:15:18.560 --> 00:15:19.760
And he'd. um…

282
00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:23.440
[sighs]

283
00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:26.080
He'd cheer me on and everything. but…

284
00:15:26.920 --> 00:15:28.240
[sighs]

285
00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:31.760
But when I… I'd fuck up. he'd just…

286
00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:33.520
[sighs]

287
00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:39.400
[exhales heavily]

288
00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:46.120
[sighs]

289
00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:49.560
He'd… He'd just look away.

290
00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:53.480
[Briony] Pretend he didn't see?

291
00:15:56.280 --> 00:15:57.800
Maybe. or…

292
00:15:58.320 --> 00:15:59.440
[clears throat]

293
00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:03.680
[sighs] Maybe he just didn't want me
to see him looking…

294
00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:05.640
[sighs. hesitates] …sorry.

295
00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:07.440
Sorry?

296
00:16:09.160 --> 00:16:10.360
I dunno.

297
00:16:11.480 --> 00:16:12.560
Ashamed.

298
00:16:16.720 --> 00:16:19.280
How did you feel when you saw that shame?

299
00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:23.760
- You're supposed to say he wasn't.
- Am I?

300
00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:25.280
Yeah.

301
00:16:25.960 --> 00:16:28.560
You're supposed to say.
"Oh. bet he wasn't ashamed."

302
00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:30.120
"Bet you just thought that. Jamie."

303
00:16:30.200 --> 00:16:34.000
Or. "Is that what you really think?
He wouldn't be ashamed. not of his kid."

304
00:16:34.080 --> 00:16:37.240
- Have other people said that to you?
- It's just the right thing to say.

305
00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:38.520
Isn't it lying?

306
00:16:38.600 --> 00:16:39.600
No.

307
00:16:40.120 --> 00:16:42.240
[sighs] I don't know. I don't like lying.

308
00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:47.880
[sighs]

309
00:16:51.560 --> 00:16:53.640
I wasn't into school sports either.

310
00:16:55.800 --> 00:16:59.240
Yeah. well. you were good
at other stuff. though. weren't ya?

311
00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:01.040
Why do you think that?

312
00:17:02.760 --> 00:17:04.400
You look like you were. and you're…

313
00:17:04.920 --> 00:17:06.120
And you're clever. so…

314
00:17:06.600 --> 00:17:09.280
Did you not think
you were very good at anything else?

315
00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:13.320
No. I… I didn't care I wasn't.

316
00:17:14.240 --> 00:17:16.160
It must be hard to feel that way.

317
00:17:16.680 --> 00:17:17.600
No.

318
00:17:18.920 --> 00:17:20.560
I think most people think like that.

319
00:17:21.080 --> 00:17:23.080
Most people think
they're bad at everything?

320
00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:24.520
Most people are.

321
00:17:25.200 --> 00:17:26.800
Does your sister feel like that?

322
00:17:27.520 --> 00:17:28.440
No.

323
00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:30.120
Lisa's clever.

324
00:17:30.640 --> 00:17:31.800
Your dad?

325
00:17:33.520 --> 00:17:34.680
I don't know.

326
00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:37.200
My… My mum does. though.

327
00:17:37.720 --> 00:17:39.800
Your mum thinks she's bad at everything?

328
00:17:40.760 --> 00:17:42.520
She can cook a roast. but…

329
00:17:43.040 --> 00:17:44.720
I mean. you'd have to ask her.

330
00:17:46.640 --> 00:17:47.640
Have you met them yet?

331
00:17:47.720 --> 00:17:49.280
- Your family?
- Yeah.

332
00:17:49.360 --> 00:17:51.480
I've… spoken to your dad on the phone.

333
00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.040
- Yeah?
- Yes. As part of my assessment.

334
00:17:54.120 --> 00:17:55.240
How is he?

335
00:17:55.320 --> 00:17:58.360
He's okay. He's sad you're here.
I can't say more than that.

336
00:17:58.440 --> 00:17:59.600
[Jamie sighs]

337
00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:03.680
[exhales]

338
00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:06.600
Well. it… it's wrong…

339
00:18:06.680 --> 00:18:07.560
[sighs]

340
00:18:07.640 --> 00:18:08.680
…that I'm in here.

341
00:18:12.320 --> 00:18:14.240
[sighs] Can I ask you a question?

342
00:18:14.880 --> 00:18:15.960
Of course you can.

343
00:18:17.040 --> 00:18:20.640
- Can you get me out of this place?
- I'm afraid I'm of no use to you there.

344
00:18:20.720 --> 00:18:23.280
Why couldn't they
put me in a proper prison?

345
00:18:23.360 --> 00:18:25.920
- A better facility wasn't available.
- Putting me in a madhouse?

346
00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.440
- It's a secure training center.
- Training?

347
00:18:29.040 --> 00:18:31.120
[hesitates] What are they training us for?

348
00:18:31.200 --> 00:18:33.160
The other boys just scream all the time.

349
00:18:33.240 --> 00:18:36.000
They rock backwards and forwards.
and they shout at Coronation Street.

350
00:18:36.080 --> 00:18:37.600
All the way through Corrie.

351
00:18:37.680 --> 00:18:41.080
One kid goes nuts every time
he sees Steve McDonald. It's mad in here.

352
00:18:41.160 --> 00:18:44.480
- [Briony] This was the best place for you.
- Ryan gets to stay home until his trial.

353
00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:46.560
[Briony] Ryan isn't accused
of such a serious crime.

354
00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:49.280
<i>Accused</i>. It's all accused.

355
00:18:49.360 --> 00:18:52.320
If I did it. if I hurt her.
then I'd get it. but I didn't. so--

356
00:18:52.400 --> 00:18:56.080
- [Briony] As far as I understand it--
- Am I getting moved for the trial?

357
00:18:56.160 --> 00:18:57.520
Nothing has been decided yet.

358
00:18:57.600 --> 00:19:00.000
Do you know where it's gonna be?
London or local?

359
00:19:00.080 --> 00:19:03.160
You need to sit down. Jamie.
If you don't sit down. I have--

360
00:19:03.240 --> 00:19:05.320
You don't know. or you just won't tell me?

361
00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:07.720
Nothing's been decided yet.
You need to sit down!

362
00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:08.640
I don't want to sit!

363
00:19:08.720 --> 00:19:10.760
If you don't sit.
I have to stop this discussion.

364
00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:12.720
- Maybe I want you to!
- Do you?

365
00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:15.920
It'd piss you off. You'd have to go home
and then come back again.

366
00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:17.600
Jamie. if you do not sit--

367
00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:20.000
I don't fucking wanna sit down!

368
00:19:20.080 --> 00:19:23.120
You do not tell me when to sit down!

369
00:19:23.200 --> 00:19:25.520
You do not control what I fucking…

370
00:19:25.600 --> 00:19:27.880
Look at me now! [panting]

371
00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:30.840
You do not control what I do in my life!

372
00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:33.040
Get that
in that fucking little head of yours!

373
00:19:33.120 --> 00:19:34.320
[door opens]

374
00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:35.560
[Jamie] Fucking hell!

375
00:19:35.640 --> 00:19:37.080
[guard] Is everything okay?

376
00:19:38.640 --> 00:19:40.160
[Jamie sighs]

377
00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:41.520
[grunts]

378
00:19:41.600 --> 00:19:43.200
- There isn't a problem.
- Fuck.

379
00:19:44.920 --> 00:19:45.840
Jamie.

380
00:19:46.760 --> 00:19:47.960
[inhales sharply]

381
00:19:48.040 --> 00:19:50.520
I shouted. I'm sorry.

382
00:19:52.480 --> 00:19:53.840
- Do you want him taken out?
- No.

383
00:19:53.920 --> 00:19:56.440
I'll get a cup of tea.
though. if that's okay.

384
00:19:58.200 --> 00:20:00.080
Can I have another hot chocolate. please?

385
00:20:01.560 --> 00:20:03.160
- Sure.
- [Jamie] You don't have to.

386
00:20:03.240 --> 00:20:04.200
Sure.

387
00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:07.880
- [somber. oppressive music rises]
- [indistinct shouting in distance]

388
00:20:26.320 --> 00:20:27.480
[exhales sharply]

389
00:20:29.720 --> 00:20:31.040
[huffs]

390
00:20:33.840 --> 00:20:35.080
[sighs]

391
00:20:42.960 --> 00:20:44.440
[man] Causing trouble. is he?

392
00:20:45.760 --> 00:20:46.880
[sighs]

393
00:20:50.200 --> 00:20:51.880
Uh. could I look in the room?

394
00:20:52.400 --> 00:20:54.640
- There's no audio.
- That's fine. Can I look?

395
00:20:54.720 --> 00:20:58.760
Of course. <i>Mi casa </i>is your <i>casa</i>.
Or whatever they say. [chuckles]

396
00:20:58.840 --> 00:21:00.440
[excited chatter nearby]

397
00:21:04.537 --> 00:21:06.200
- [man] After you.
- Thank you.

398
00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:22.120
What are you seeing?

399
00:21:24.160 --> 00:21:28.120
I mean. what is it you're looking for?
Is it body language stuff?

400
00:21:30.600 --> 00:21:32.800
It's just. I'm reading a book
on that at the moment.

401
00:21:36.880 --> 00:21:38.680
My sister gave it to me.

402
00:21:41.200 --> 00:21:42.120
You see.

403
00:21:43.880 --> 00:21:44.840
people hide.

404
00:21:45.880 --> 00:21:51.160
I know I don't need to tell you this.
but… they hide so much.

405
00:21:53.033 --> 00:21:56.153
Maybe they tell the truth
with their bodies. hm?

406
00:21:57.480 --> 00:21:59.320
- Faces--
- [curtly] Yes. maybe.

407
00:22:03.280 --> 00:22:04.680
I couldn't do what you do.

408
00:22:05.200 --> 00:22:07.080
I'm sure I couldn't do what you do.

409
00:22:07.600 --> 00:22:09.080
Do you want to job swap?

410
00:22:09.760 --> 00:22:10.920
What's your hours?

411
00:22:11.440 --> 00:22:13.400
What's your wages? [chuckles]

412
00:22:13.480 --> 00:22:17.440
- What's your holiday allowance?
- No. I like my job most of the time.

413
00:22:18.640 --> 00:22:21.520
Well… I hate mine.

414
00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:25.000
So you're probably best off.

415
00:22:27.480 --> 00:22:28.360
Right.

416
00:22:29.080 --> 00:22:30.280
That's all I needed.

417
00:22:30.800 --> 00:22:31.640
Dib dib dib.

418
00:22:32.520 --> 00:22:34.200
- Pleased to help.
- Thank you.

419
00:22:35.120 --> 00:22:36.080
Thanks.

420
00:22:42.080 --> 00:22:43.440
[exhales deeply]

421
00:22:44.200 --> 00:22:45.200
[clears throat]

422
00:22:49.440 --> 00:22:50.800
[exhales sharply]

423
00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:53.880
[guard] Would you be comfortable
with me staying?

424
00:22:53.960 --> 00:22:56.000
No. I wouldn't like that at all.

425
00:22:56.080 --> 00:23:00.760
Right. Jamie. I'm not a police officer.
I'm not here to elicit a confession.

426
00:23:00.840 --> 00:23:05.000
I'm just here to understand.
I know you think I'm trying to trick you.

427
00:23:05.080 --> 00:23:06.840
I said… I said that ages ago.

428
00:23:06.920 --> 00:23:10.480
I am just here to get an understanding
of your understanding.

429
00:23:13.160 --> 00:23:15.040
[sighs] And I understand

430
00:23:16.080 --> 00:23:19.000
that you need to have an understanding
of my understanding.

431
00:23:20.720 --> 00:23:21.880
Go on.

432
00:23:22.840 --> 00:23:23.960
Ask your questions.

433
00:23:24.720 --> 00:23:26.280
[sighs] I will be better now.

434
00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:29.320
[exhales]

435
00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:32.640
Okay. Uh…

436
00:23:36.440 --> 00:23:41.840
Well. I suppose the other thing I think of
in relation to the word "masculinity"

437
00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:45.000
would be how masculine men
feel about women.

438
00:23:46.240 --> 00:23:48.600
- We're back on that. are we?
- Yes. Is that okay?

439
00:23:49.920 --> 00:23:51.520
[sighs] Yeah.

440
00:23:52.600 --> 00:23:55.720
You need to have an understanding
of my understanding of women.

441
00:23:56.200 --> 00:23:58.200
- I forgot your hot chocolate.
- It's fine.

442
00:23:58.280 --> 00:24:01.280
- I'll get it.
- No. just… sit down. please.

443
00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:02.920
[sighs]

444
00:24:03.880 --> 00:24:05.760
It's fine. I don't deserve it.

445
00:24:05.840 --> 00:24:06.960
I shouted.

446
00:24:09.080 --> 00:24:11.680
Ask your questions
about men. women. whatever.

447
00:24:13.680 --> 00:24:16.320
Well. you must have views
on men and women.

448
00:24:17.440 --> 00:24:19.120
How does your dad treat your mum?

449
00:24:20.720 --> 00:24:23.440
- Are you trying to get at my dad again?
- No. not get at him.

450
00:24:24.280 --> 00:24:25.720
Dad's actually nice to Mum.

451
00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:27.280
You did say he tore down a shed.

452
00:24:27.360 --> 00:24:30.360
Yeah. he just gets angry with himself.
but he's never hit her.

453
00:24:30.440 --> 00:24:32.040
Does he speak to other women?

454
00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:34.480
- What?
- Is he friendly with other women?

455
00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:37.160
What? No. He loves my mum.

456
00:24:37.240 --> 00:24:39.840
No. I'm asking
whether any of his friends are women.

457
00:24:40.440 --> 00:24:43.440
No. his mates are his mates.

458
00:24:43.520 --> 00:24:44.560
And they're men?

459
00:24:45.120 --> 00:24:46.880
Is that wrong? What does that mean?

460
00:24:46.960 --> 00:24:49.000
No. No. that's not wrong.

461
00:24:50.720 --> 00:24:52.520
I thought we'd done talking about my dad.

462
00:24:52.600 --> 00:24:55.160
- Jamie. I'm just trying to understand--
- Understand.

463
00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:58.720
I know. but… none of this
is nothing to do with him.

464
00:24:59.600 --> 00:25:01.600
- [sighs]
- Okay. that's fine.

465
00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:04.680
- Do <i>you </i>have any mates who are women?
- No.

466
00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.320
Like your dad. your mates are male?

467
00:25:09.520 --> 00:25:13.480
[sighs] The other shrink asks
more normal questions. you know?

468
00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:15.080
- Okay.
- Wanna know what he asks?

469
00:25:15.160 --> 00:25:17.320
- I can't know.
- [scoffs] I'm just saying.

470
00:25:17.400 --> 00:25:20.280
I can't know. Jamie.
My conclusions have to be independent.

471
00:25:20.360 --> 00:25:22.400
All right. okay. I won't say anything.

472
00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:25.600
What do you think about women?

473
00:25:26.680 --> 00:25:27.680
I like them.

474
00:25:27.760 --> 00:25:30.480
But you're not. like you say.
particularly friends with them?

475
00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:32.120
I'm not a twat. though.

476
00:25:32.200 --> 00:25:35.120
- Are you attracted to women?
- Yeah. I'm not gay.

477
00:25:35.680 --> 00:25:38.280
We've established
you don't have a girlfriend.

478
00:25:38.360 --> 00:25:40.600
- Yeah.
- But I don't think I asked before.

479
00:25:40.680 --> 00:25:42.240
Would you <i>like </i>a girlfriend?

480
00:25:42.320 --> 00:25:43.520
Yeah. who doesn't?

481
00:25:44.040 --> 00:25:46.440
If you had a girlfriend.
what would you do with her?

482
00:25:46.520 --> 00:25:47.960
[hesitates] What does that mean?

483
00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:51.640
Well. would you take her out?
If you did. where would you take her?

484
00:25:54.400 --> 00:25:55.680
[sighs] The cinema.

485
00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:58.520
To see what kind of film?

486
00:26:01.600 --> 00:26:02.440
A horror.

487
00:26:03.600 --> 00:26:04.800
Fifteen certificate?

488
00:26:05.680 --> 00:26:09.160
Mm. Yeah. they're pretty slack.
You can get in.

489
00:26:10.040 --> 00:26:11.880
And after the cinema. would you

490
